  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony under both U.S. federal law and the laws of most states. Money laundering involves engaging in financial transactions to conceal the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial dealings. It is a serious crime that undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates other criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, tax evasion, and fraud.\n\n### Penalties for Money Laundering:\n- under the **U.S. federal Money Laundering Control Act (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957)**, individuals convicted of money laundering can face:\n  - **Up to 20 years in federal prison** for each offense.\n  - **Fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater.\n  - Forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering scheme.\n- Penalties can be even more severe if the laundering is tied to terrorism, drug trafficking, or other serious crimes.\n- State laws also impose felony charges and penalties for money laundering, which vary by jurisdiction.\n\nIn addition to criminal penalties, individuals and businesses involved in money laundering may face civil fines and reputational damage. Financial institutions are also required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs to prevent and report suspicious activities.",
